Bay District Schools
August 22 at 8:26 AM ¬∑

Parents/Guardians: We've had an AMAZING first two days and we appreciate your support. We've been so pleased with the number of students who are wearing masks and doing their best to social distance. Please take a few minutes this weekend to remind your students that those measures enhance their safety AND the safety of their friends and teachers. We appreciate you taking the time to encourage your students to wear their masks, wash their hands and keep their social distance when possible. When it comes to masks, please remember that we are committed to flexibility with our younger students and students with medical exemptions need only to turn in that documentation. #Community

The College Board
March 16 at 1:26 PM ¬∑

The College Board is developing tools to mitigate the impact of school closures on students in the Advanced Placement Program. All AP students and teachers will be able to draw on the free online resources that were provided to every AP classroom this fall. Additional resources will be made easily accessible to AP students and teachers through mobile phones and other devices. These include free online AP lessons and review sessions from some of the top AP teachers in the country.

The AP program is finalizing streamlined AP exam options that would allow students to test at home, depending on the situation in May. We‚Äôre working to give every AP student the opportunity to claim the credit they‚Äôve earned. The AP Program will communicate the details of these additional solutions to educators and students by March 20.

The College Board‚Äôs focus will remain on student safety and ensuring all students have the tools they need to work, and opportunities to receive the credit they have earned, during this challenging time.

More details: http://spr.ly/61861srPq.

shared_text:
Bay District Schools
March 13 at 3:59 PM ¬∑

Per instructions we just received on a conference call from DOE with all
superintendents, all Bay District non-charter schools (including Haney) will be closed March 16-20 for Spring Break and then March 23-27. This closure is going on statewide. During the two-week closure, all schools will undergo additional disinfecting and sanitizing in preparation for the return of students and staff. Bay Base will be open, as previously scheduled, during Spring Break for those families who registered but it will not be open March 23-27 at any location. All extra-curricular activities, including field trips, are cancelled until at least March 27th. All of these plans are subject to change, per the DOE, and we will release more details as we have them. All 12-month employees should report to work as regularly scheduled on March 23rd and await further instructions.

post_text: Awwwww!
shared_text:
Bay District Schools is feeling blessed.
November 13, 2019 at 8:59 PM ¬∑

Sometimes the kindness of strangers is simply overwhelming. We ordered about $20,000 worth of clearance jackets from Smith and Davis Clothing in Georgia (retail value easily five times that) and they had arranged free delivery for us for Saturday. After seeing the weather reports, the 80-year-old patriarch of the family-owned business offered to make the six-hour trek today so our kids could get jackets sooner! We are humbled by the kindness, compassion and generosity of this business and their continued commitment to our community. You, my friends, are true #HurricaneHeroes.

Coach Tillman believes in helping those in our community. During our October home football game our cheerleaders and Arnold's cheerleaders passed a helmet around to collect donations. Today a Ram cheerleader and a Ram varsity football player presented a check to Ms. Serenity Anderson and her husband. She is a RHS alum and is currently battling breast cancer.
